IV.—METRES AND PROSODY.

(1) In giving 3 short account of the Metres and Prosody of Plautus, it must not be overlooked that he is not only the earliest Latin writer whose works we possess, but also, we may say, the earliest exponent of Latin literature of every class, and is certainly to be placed at the head 01 his own department, as well in point of time as in the general excellence of his work.
